,\"text\":\"**Considering class loading issues**\\n\\nI’m thinking about how if the child TraceFactory calls Class.forName on a custom nested within the parent, it could lead to a ClassCastException because the class isn’t assignable to the child TraceFactory. So, the custom factory needs to be either generated as bytecode for the child loader or exist as a test class that references the child TraceFactory. Since the classpath includes test classes, the child-first classloader could load a duplicate copy of the nested CustomTraceFactory and TraceFactoryTest. I need the custom class to be public!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Clarifying test order**\\n\\nI’m looking through prior test results, and I think it’s possible that a class named `ATraceFactoryTest` runs before `AjTypeImplTest`. I’m comparing the alphabetical order of \\\"ATrace\\\" and \\\"Aj.\\\" Since 'T' (84) is less than 'j' (106), it seems like `ATrace` comes before `Aj`. But \\\"TraceFactoryTest\\\" definitely appears after that. The user probably expects the active class file to be named `TraceFactoryTest`.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering test class naming**\\n\\nI’m thinking about naming the active test class. Calling it `AAATraceFactoryTest` seems a bit odd. Maybe `TraceFactoryTest` would work better, especially with the potential for using `@TestClassOrder` from JUnit 5. But I wonder if that applies at the suite level rather than per class. I’ll need to check if Gradle can sort or if there’s already a mechanism for ordering test classes. I'll look into the root build.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_0ijFcS6lSkIT8xi561dJUFxB|fc_064330bd950863460169f181b4af78819396c30e3680cde652", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "rg \"scanForTestClasses|TestClass|classOrder|junit|include \\\"\\*\" -n build.gradle gradle tests/src/org.aspectj/aspectjweaver/1.9.7 settings.gradle", "timeout": 10}, "partialJson": "{\"command\":\"rg \\\"scanForTestClasses|TestClass|cla